         <div xml:id="main">
            <head type="incipit">
               <supplied reason="XTF-compatibility">25, WILTON PLACE, S.W. ¶ June 18 /68 ¶ My dear Sir ¶  ¶ Since I last wrote the three vessels in which you sent the remaining Monopetalae have arrived safely — in the inverse order in which they sailed...</supplied>
            </head>
            <p rend="number" xml:lang="en">68.06.18c</p>
            <p rend="correspondent" xml:lang="en">From George Bentham</p>
            <p rend="location" xml:lang="en">RB MSS M4, Library, Royal Botanic Gardens Melbourne.</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <seg rend="form%20text" style="color: #2f5496; font-family: Times, Times; ">25, WILTON PLACE, S.W.</seg>
            </p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; text-align: end; "
               xml:lang="en">June 18 /68</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">My dear Sir</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Since I last wrote the three vessels in which you sent the remaining <name key="Monopetalae">Monopetalae</name> have arrived safely — in the inverse order in which they sailed the Great Britain first then the Norfolk and lastly the Dover Castle the boxes were rather long clearing but those from the Great Britain which were the longest reached Kew last week — all as far as I have seen in good condition. — I sent you some sheets of the new volume by this mail via Southampton but waited to write as I had not yet the Great Britain boxes — you have I supposed received from Kew the bill of lading of the <name key="Epacrideae">Epacrideae</name> etc which were sent some time since. — Another box will be ready in a few days with a few parcels that would not go into the last one and some others I have now done with.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I had just got through <name key="Convolvulaceae">Convolvulaceae</name> when these boxes arrived and since then I have been revising with your specimens — the correcting proofs checking references etc also takes up much of my time — besides that I have had to devote a good deal of time to the Linnean Society especially to my annual address and other not very scientific business</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Your <name key="Thozetia">Thozetia</name> can I believe stand I have at any rate adopted it. It is however very near <name key="Hoya">Hoya</name> — several Asiatic species of which have membranous leaves.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I am afraid <name key="Maccoya">Maccoya</name> will not do You observed how near it is to Rochelia<note xml:id="ftn1" type="footnote" n="1">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>B59.04.04, p. 127.</p>
               </note> and one of Boissiers Rochelias has the same multiplication of calycine lobes — the habit is quite the same.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I duly received yours of 29th March.<note xml:id="ftn2" type="footnote" n="2">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>M to G. Bentham, 29 March 1868.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note> With regard to your observations on genera I can only say that if you can find "some firm character by which at a moment we could <seg style="">
                  <hi rend="underline">firmly</hi>
               </seg> find out the limits" of a large genus — or at least of the great majority of large genera you would render a great service to science. I find all characters of genera tribes and Orders occasionally break down in intermediate or abnormal species. There is certainly no character without exception for <name key="Acacia">Acacia</name>
               <name key="Eugenia">Eugenia</name>
               <name key="Aster">Aster</name>
               <name key="Solanum">Solanum</name>
               <name key="Salvia">Salvia</name> etc — at least I have always found here and there species which pass into other groups</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>I fear I shall not get all the <name key="Monopetalae">Monopetalae</name> into the present volume. The numbers grow upon me more than I foresaw — and there are still no doubt many more tropical ones. At any rate you need be in no hurry to send any <name key="Monochlamydeae">Monochlamydeae</name>. I shall certainly not be able to begin them till next spring — and at my age life is so uncertain that I may never come to them.</p>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>Hooker is at work at the Genera<note xml:id="ftn3" type="footnote" n="3">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>
                     </seg>Bentham &amp; Hooker (1862-83).</p>
               </note> and I shall have to do something towards it this winter — one thing prevents our hurrying that on is that it is a heavy expense to us. My income is not large and the Linnean Society entails considerable expense so that I cannot afford much for pure science. We hope however to print a part in the spring<note xml:id="ftn4" type="footnote" n="4">
                  <p rend="Footnote"
                     style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; margin-left: 0.3335in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: -0.3335in; font-size: 9pt; "
                     xml:lang="en">
                     <space unit="chars" quantity="1"/>
                     <seg style="">
                        <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>No new part of the </seg>
                     <seg style="font-style: italic; ">Genera</seg>
                     <seg style=""> was published until 1873.</seg>
                  </p>
               </note>
            </p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">Ever yours sincerely</p>
            <p rend="valediction"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; margin-left: 1.75in; margin-right: 0in; text-indent: 0in; "
               xml:lang="en">
               <space dim="horizontal" extent="tab"/>George Bentham</p>
            <space dim="vertical" unit="lines" quantity="1"/>
            <p rend="letter"
               style="font-family: Geneva, Geneva; font-size: 12pt; "
               xml:lang="en">Dr F. Mueller</p>
